TY  - JOUR
T1  - Social Networks and Perceptions of Intergroup Conflict: The Role of Negative Relationships and Third Parties
AU  - Labianca, Giuseppe
AU  - Brass, Daniel J.
AU  - Gray, Barbara
Y1  - 1998/02/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256897
DO  - 10.5465/256897
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 55
EP  - 67
VL  - 41
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study investigated the relationship between interpersonal relationships among members of different departments and individuals' perceptions of intergroup conflict within an organization. Although friendships across groups were not significantly related to perceptions of intergroup conflict, negative relationships were associated with higher perceived intergroup conflict. Perceptions of intergroup conflict were also significantly related to indirect relationships through friends, and an amplification effect was uncovered. Finally, low intragroup cohesiveness was significantly related to higher perceptions of intergroup conflict.
AB  - This study investigated the relationship between interpersonal relationships among members of different departments and individuals' perceptions of intergroup conflict within an organization. Although friendships across groups were not significantly related to perceptions of intergroup conflict, negative relationships were associated with higher perceived intergroup conflict. Perceptions of intergroup conflict were also significantly related to indirect relationships through friends, and an amplification effect was uncovered. Finally, low intragroup cohesiveness was significantly related to higher perceptions of intergroup conflict.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256897
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256897
